	abstract = {Plant breeding is being used as an environmentally sound approach to increase food production and ensure food security. However, in order to boost crop yields and produce new varieties that are more resilient to various environmental stress factors and more nutritious, various high-throughput multi-omics strategies in plant breeding have been developed and implemented. These cutting-edge technologies are used to produce huge amounts of data about the plants' phenotype, biochemistry, physiology and genetic architecture, and could be used to manipulate the essential traits of plants, which are crucial for crop improvement. Therefore, in order to analyse and represent these enormous amounts of complicated data in an efficient way, plant breeders usually depend on advanced computational and bioinformatics tools and artificial intelligence (AI), including machine learning (ML) techniques. These technologies could also be used for plant phenotyping and genomic prediction for the efficient selection of superior plant types. Artificial intelligence refers to the ability of machines, in particular, computers, to simulate human intelligence processes. To write and operate machine learning algorithms, AI needs a foundation of sophisticated software and hardware components. The application of AI to plant breeding can provide breeders with highly productive and useful tools to accelerate the development of improved crop varieties and enhance the effectiveness of the breeding processes, which are crucial for addressing the difficulties that agriculture currently faces in the age of climate change. This chapter briefly explains how AI could revolutionize the field of future plant breeding while addressing the global food security and nutritional requirements. © CAB International 2025. All rights reserved.},
