	year = {2003},
	journal = {Novenytermeles},
	volume = {52},
	number = {6},
	pages = {609 – 621},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-33748924150&partnerID=40&md5=cc43c323a19d3c7eadb3ea404ce8a505},
	affiliations = {Debreceni Egyetem, Agrártudományi Centrum, Debrecen, Hungary; Centre for Agricultural Sciences, University of Debrecen, Debrecen, Hungary; Debreceni Egyetem Agrártudományi, Centrum Genetikai és Nemesítés Tanszék, Debrecem H-4015, Pf.: 36, Hungary},
	abstract = {Due to specific breeding aims and gene erosion the genetic basis of maize breeding has decreased significantly in Hungary in recent decades, with well-known unfavourable effects. Many foreign hybrids are used in maize production, the genetic background of which is restricted a few inbred lines. In order to decrease the genetic vulnerability, it is very important to widen the base for maize breeding using various methods. One way of increasing genetic variability is through treatment with various mutagens. Within a programme started in 1979-80, F1 maize hybrid seeds were treated with radiation from the Co60 isotope. Later, in 1985, the trial was expanded and the seeds were treated with radiation from fast neutrons at the Atomic Research Institute of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences in Debrecen. Selected mutant lines developed in this way have been self-pollinated for several years. These homogeneous lines formed the plant material in the present trials, based on two complete diallel systems ('A' and 'B'). The two diallel systems were examined by applying a modified version of the DIALLEL Analysis and Simulation programme (BUROW-COORS, 1993), according to the GRIPPING 1 method (1956). In the case of diallel system 'A', line A13 and its hybrids (A3 and A10) had the highest combining abilities, compared to the standard and the other hybrids, and produced outstanding yields in all three years examined. Lines B15 and B16, which had excellent GCA, were always found among the parents of hybrids B3, B6, B9 and B10, which had outstanding productivity. This was proved by the results of all the three years. Due to the low productivity observed in all three years, hybrids B1 and B4 and their parent lines, which had low GCA values, were eliminated from further breeding projects. The others were able to equal or exceed the productivity of the standard hybrid in all three years, so the best of them will be subjected to further testing and, if satisfactory results arc obtained, in the development of new hybrids in the future.},
	author_keywords = {Diallel analysis; Fast neutron; General combining ability (GCA); Mutation breeding of maize (Zea mays L.); Plant breeding; Specific combining ability (SCA)},
